{
    "analysis": "None",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Load metric.csv, trace.csv, log.csv, and error_logs.csv from the current directory. For each file, return a compact summary only: (1) total row count; (2) min and max timestamp values; (3) list of unique cmdb_id values (limit to first 50); (4) list of unique KPI/trace/log names (for metric use kpi_name, for trace use trace_name, for log use log_name) with their counts, limited to top 50 by frequency; (5) display up to the first 5 rows as examples (showing all columns). Keep outputs concise and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "Previous step computed global P95 thresholds (from full series) and counted per-(component,KPI) anomalies inside the incident window. Results show many persistent anomalies across the whole window for several KPIs: Redis maxmemory-related KPIs (Redis01/Redis02) and JVM HeapMemoryMax (IG01/IG02, MG02) show 31 anomalies (one per minute), Tomcat request MaxTime and MaxThreads KPIs show 31 anomalies as well. Trace-side anomalies show spikes in row_count and duration_p95 for several containers/services with earliest anomaly timestamps clustered around 22:00, 22:03, 22:06 and 22:13. Logs are empty so they cannot be used.\n\nWhat we need next: determine which of these persistent anomalies constitute real faults (consecutive anomaly streaks, and significant severity breaches). Also correlate metric faults with trace faults to pick the most downstream faulty service where multiple services at same level appear faulty. To do that we must compute for each candidate (from the prior top anomaly tables) the severity ratio ((max_value_in_window - global_threshold)/global_threshold) and the longest consecutive anomaly streak length inside the window and the earliest timestamp of that streak. This will let us filter out weak/false-positive KPI flags (small breaches) and to identify distinct fault start times. We will do this for the top metric anomaly candidates and top trace anomaly candidates (limit to 20 rows each) so we can localize two distinct failures and their root causes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel variables metric_result and trace_result (the aggregated anomaly tables computed before), compute for each row the following additional fields using the already-filtered-in-window data cached in the kernel: (1) severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_threshold) / global_threshold (use NaN or -inf if global_threshold is zero); (2) longest_consecutive_anomaly_length within the window for that (component,KPI) time series (i.e., longest run of consecutive timestamps where value >= global_threshold); (3) earliest_timestamp_of_longest_run (the timestamp of the first point of that longest consecutive run). Produce two compact tables (limit 20 rows each), one for metric_result and one for trace_result, sorted by longest_consecutive_anomaly_length descending then severity_ratio descending. Columns to return: cmdb_id, kpi_name (or trace_name), global_threshold, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio, longest_consecutive_anomaly_length, earliest_timestamp_of_longest_run, anomaly_count_in_window, total_points_in_window. If any global_threshold is zero, mark severity_ratio as null and still return the row. Keep outputs bounded to top 20 rows each."
}

{
    "analysis": "We computed global P95 thresholds from the full series and found many metric KPIs that are exactly at their P95 (severity_ratio = 0) across the whole 31-minute window; thus metrics alone do not contain strong positive-severity faults to single out a root cause. Trace analysis found several trace KPIs with non-zero severity_ratio and finite consecutive anomaly runs (e.g., dockerB2.trace.self.duration_p95 with longest run = 5 starting 22:01, MG02/Tomcat01 related trace.to/from entries with strong severity starting 22:06, MG01-related traces around 22:07 and later). Because there are multiple candidate trace anomalies with different start times (clustered around ~22:01 and ~22:06), the two failures likely correspond to at least two distinct trace-fault clusters. Logs are empty so we must rely on traces and metrics correlation. Next we should extract the exact anomaly timestamps for the top trace candidates (those with non-zero severity_ratio) so we can cluster anomalies into distinct failure events and then use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service in each cluster.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "From the trace time-series (full kernel dataframe) and the previously computed per-(cmdb_id,trace_name) global thresholds, select the top 10 trace candidates by severity_ratio (non-zero) from the augmented trace table. For each selected (cmdb_id, trace_name), return a compact aggregate with these columns: cmdb_id, trace_name, global_threshold, anomaly_timestamps_in_window (list of timestamps where value >= global_threshold, limited to first 20 timestamps), earliest_anomaly_timestamp, anomaly_count_in_window. Limit the output to those top 10 candidates and keep the response bounded. If any candidate has no anomaly timestamps (unexpected), include it with an empty list and note it."
}

{
    "analysis": "We inspected trace anomalies (top candidates by severity) and found multiple small clusters of anomaly timestamps across the window. Key observations: (1) several trace anomaly groups have earliest timestamps around 22:01; (2) another cluster around 22:05–22:13; (3) a later cluster around 22:18–22:29. Logs are empty and many metric KPIs show full-window values equal to their P95 (severity_ratio=0), so metrics do not clearly single out a root cause. Therefore we must use traces to (a) identify which two distinct time clusters correspond to the two detected failures and (b) for each failure pick the most downstream faulty component by trace call relationships.\n\nWhat to do next: compute minute-level aggregation of all trace anomalies (using global thresholds previously computed) inside the incident window to identify the minutes with highest anomaly concentration and list the involved components and trace_names for those minutes. This will let us map the two failure events to exact occurrence minutes and the candidate faulty components active at those minutes.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel trace dataframe and the per-(cmdb_id,trace_name) global thresholds already calculated, produce a compact minute-level aggregation for the window timestamps >=1614866400 and <=1614868200: for each timestamp (minute) compute (1) total number of trace anomaly points at that minute (value >= global_threshold), (2) list of distinct cmdb_id values involved at that minute (limit to first 10), and (3) list of distinct trace_name values involved at that minute (limit to first 10). Return the top 10 minutes sorted by total anomaly count descending. Also return, for each of those top minutes, the full set of (cmdb_id, trace_name) pairs that were anomalous at that minute but limit the output to at most 50 pairs overall. Keep the output compact and bounded."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have proceeded through threshold calculation and anomaly detection. metric.csv and trace.csv were summarized; log files are empty. Global P95 thresholds were computed from full series. Metric-side many component-KPI pairs (Redis memory, JVM HeapMax, Tomcat request MaxTime/Threads) show values equal to their P95 across the entire 31-minute window (severity_ratio = 0), so metrics alone do not provide high-severity, short-lived faults. Trace analysis revealed concentrated anomaly minutes: a cluster near 22:01 (2021-03-04 22:01:00+08:00, ts=1614866460) with ~22 anomalous trace rows involving MG02, dockerA1/A2, dockerB1/B2, and another stronger cluster near 22:06 (2021-03-04 22:06:00+08:00, ts=1614866760) with ~70 anomalous trace rows heavily involving Tomcat01, Tomcat03, IG01/IG02, MG01/MG02 and showing high severities (e.g., Tomcat01 -> MG02 duration_p95 severity >1.4). For 22:01 the top trace target was MG02 (mostly 'from' entries) and several 'to' relations to dockerA2/dockerB2 appeared; for 22:06 the most anomalous target services were Tomcat01 and Tomcat03 with high-severity to/from relations to MG02. Logs are empty so we must correlate traces with metrics to localize root cause components. The next step should be metric confirmation: check detailed per-KPI anomalies (global P95, anomaly counts, longest consecutive runs, earliest run timestamp, severity ratios) for a focused set of candidate components implicated by traces so we can determine which component(s) show real resource faults (severity > ~50% breach and consecutive anomalies) at 22:01 and 22:06. This will let us pick the most downstream faulty service as root cause per failure.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "Using the kernel metric dataframe (metric.csv) and the already-computed global thresholds for each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair, analyze the following candidate components: Tomcat01, Tomcat03, IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2. For each (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pair across the full series compute global P95 (already computed; reuse it), then filter rows to the incident window timestamps >=1614866400 and <=1614868200. For each pair return: cmdb_id, kpi_name, global_P95, anomaly_count_in_window (value >= global_P95), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_P95)/global_P95 (null if global_P95==0), longest_consecutive_anomaly_length (consecutive minutes with value >= global_P95), and earliest_timestamp_of_longest_run. Return two outputs: (A) a table of the top 20 rows across all listed components sorted by severity_ratio descending then longest_consecutive_anomaly_length descending; (B) detailed tables for Tomcat01 and MG02 listing all their (cmdb_id,kpi_name) pairs (limit to 50 rows each) with the same columns. Keep outputs compact and bounded (max 20 rows for table A, max 50 rows for each detailed table)."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have progressed through the prescribed workflow: thresholds (global P95) were computed from full series; metrics and traces were filtered to the incident window; anomaly detection found many metric KPIs at their P95 across the whole window (severity_ratio = 0) while trace anomalies formed several short bursts. Minute-level trace aggregation revealed two concentrated anomaly clusters that map to two likely failure events: one cluster around 2021-03-04 22:01:00+08:00 (ts=1614866460) and a stronger cluster around 2021-03-04 22:06:00+08:00 (ts=1614866760). Trace-level details at those minutes show: at 22:01 many anomalous pairs involve MG02 and dockerA/B nodes (MG02 appears as a frequent 'from' target), while at 22:06 many anomalies involve Tomcat01 and Tomcat03 interacting with IG01/IG02 and MG01/MG02; high-severity trace spikes (e.g., Tomcat01 -> MG02 duration_p95) occur at 22:06. Metric analysis on a focused set (Tomcat01, Tomcat03, IG01, IG02, MG01, MG02, dockerA1/A2, dockerB1/B2) found several strong metric spikes: IG02 shows very high CPU WIO and disk I/O spikes (severity_ratio up to ~5.18, earliest anomaly 22:00), MG02 shows both high-severity short spikes (CPU WIO, disk) and many full-window JVM memory KPIs equal to P95, and Tomcat instances show CPU WIO and other short spikes (severity ~0.6–1.0) with earliest anomalies around 22:01–22:06. Logs are empty so we cannot use log evidence.\n\nWhat can be derived so far: there are at least two distinct failure events (around 22:01 and 22:06). Trace anomalies at 22:06 include high-severity downstream calls to MG02 from Tomcat01 (trace.to_MG02.duration_p95 severity >1.4), suggesting either MG02 slowness causing Tomcat latencies or Tomcat experiencing issues while calling MG02. Metric severities show IG02 and MG02 have the largest metric deviations in the whole window (IG02 highest severity, earliest 22:00; MG02 also has strong disk/CPU spikes). According to the root-cause rules, if multiple candidate faults exist at different levels, choose the fault with the largest deviation (>50%) and then use traces to pick the most downstream faulty service in the call chain. To definitively map each failure to a root cause component, we need a compact per-component summary that reports the single most severe KPI (severity_ratio), its earliest anomaly timestamp in the incident window, the longest consecutive anomalous run length, and whether the severity breach is substantial (>50%). This will let us decide which fault started when and which component is the most likely root cause for each of the two failure minutes identified by trace clustering.",
    "completed": "False",
    "instruction": "For the candidate components [IG02, MG02, Tomcat01, Tomcat03, IG01, MG01, dockerA1, dockerA2, dockerB1, dockerB2], compute a compact per-component summary using metric data already loaded and global thresholds previously computed: for each component find the KPI (kpi_name) that has the maximum severity_ratio = (max_value_in_window - global_P95)/global_P95 within the incident window (timestamps >=1614866400 and <=1614868200). For that KPI return: component(cmdb_id), kpi_name, global_P95, max_value_in_window, severity_ratio (null if global_P95==0), earliest_anomaly_timestamp_in_window for that KPI (first timestamp where value >= global_P95), longest_consecutive_anomaly_length for that KPI, earliest_timestamp_of_longest_run. Also include a boolean flag severe_gt_50pct = True when severity_ratio > 0.5. Return one row per component (limit 20 rows), sorted by severity_ratio descending. Keep output compact and bounded."
}

